Authorities arrested the Howells and Vesey on August 15, and they have now been charged with intending to sexually abuse or physically harm the girls, and two counts of first-degree kidnapping. 

During a hearing on Thursday in a St Lawrence County, NY court, Vaisey revealed that she and Howell were on a 'shopping trip' for slaves.

Her attorney is claiming she was in a 'master-slave relationship' with her boyfriend, and therefore not as culpable for the crime. 

'She was the submissive one,' Vaisey's attorney, Bradford Riendeau, stated last week. 'I am currently researching on what happens when prisoners of war go through enhanced interrogation. What torture has done to her personality to determine just how compliant she was? Was it really voluntary? Can you really give consent to be tortured?'

Howells waived his right to a hearing, so that his case may go straight to a grand jury.  

